"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687009","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-20","<p>For Contracting Parties to the Bern Convention, who are Member States of the European Union, the Natura 2000 Network provides Member States’ contributions to the Emerald Network of protected areas established in accordance with the Bern Convention.</p><p> </p><p>The rules established by European Council Directives 79/409/EEC and 92/43/EEC apply to these areas until we leave the European Union. If there is a complaint that a Bern Convention Contacting Party is not complying with its Convention obligations, this matter can be brought to the attention of the Bern Convention Standing Committee.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is currently considering the impacts of leaving the EU, including future arrangements for existing legislation. This will include future arrangements for the Natura 2000 suite of sites.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687009/answer",,,,,,"2017-02-20T10:32:30.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687009/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687009/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-08","Marine Protected Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the oral evidence of the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State to the Environmental Audit Committee of 31 January 2017, what powers of oversight and enforcement the Council of Europe has in relation to monitoring marine protected areas in compliance with the Bern Convention.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","63740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687010","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-23","<p>Any commercial buyers that source fish directly from the fishing industry must be registered, comply with the obligation to submit to the UK authorities a sales note, identifying the specific vessel that caught the fish, and must comply with ongoing requirements on traceability. Failure to comply with these obligations constitutes as a criminal offence that includes an unlimited fine.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687010/answer",,,,,,"2017-02-23T15:09:22.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687010/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687010/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-08","Fisheries: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what penalties there are for (a) supplying and (b) serving illegally caught sea bass.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","63577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687011","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-20","<p>The Environment Agency is currently pursuing the former owners and operators of the Trent Valley Recycling (TVR) site and all those connected for offences under the Environmental Permitting Regulations 2010.</p><p>The Environment Agency has been working with partners from the Nottinghamshire Local Resilience Forum (LRF) to identify the risks associated with the site. The main risk to the public is the potential for the abandoned waste on site to catch fire. There is a low risk of this waste self-combusting, but there is a risk of someone gaining access to the site and deliberately setting fire to the waste which could result in a major fire. The site, however, is fenced off and the entrance secured.</p><p>Nottinghamshire Fire and Rescue Service has produced a tactical fire plan for the site, outlining the steps they would take in such an event. All partners have contributed to this plan and a Tactical Liaison Group will be established in the event of a major fire.</p><p>The Local Resilience Forum has estimated that a major fire at the site is likely to last a number of weeks. A fire at a similar site in north Nottinghamshire in October 2016 required a fire service presence for 6 weeks and cost in the region of £1.5 million. Other partners in the LRF would have costs associated with tackling a major fire also.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687011/answer",,,,,"63644 ; 63645","2017-02-20T10:23:26.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687011/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687011/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-02-08","Industrial Estates: Worksop","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether she plans to pursue enforcement action on the site owned by the Crown Estate in Worksop previously occupied by Trent Valley Recycling; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","63646"
