"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687091","Home Office","false","2017-02-20","<p>The information and evidence required in respect of employment and dividend income relied upon to meet the income threshold for partner entry clearance applications under Appendix FM to the Immigration Rules is set out in part 3 of appendix 2 to the visa application form 4A and in sections 5 and 6 of the Immigration Directorate Instructions for Appendix FM 1.7 Financial Requirement. These documents can be found at <a href="http://www.homeoffice.gov.uk/" target="_blank">www.homeoffice.gov.uk</a>.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687091/answer",,,,,"63754","2017-02-20T15:21:50.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687091/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687091/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-08","Entry Clearances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether UK Visas and Immigration plans to publish guidelines on how earnings and dividends should be presented where the income threshold is met by the sponsor for entry clearance under Appendix FM applications.","false","Biography information for Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","Tooting","Dr Rosena Allin-Khan","63753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687092","Home Office","false","2017-02-20","<p>The Home Office has not used Official Development Assistance funding to support individuals trafficked into the sex industry in the UK. Following a successful reasonable grounds decision, all potential victims of modern slavery, including those trafficked into the sex industry in the UK, are entitled to 45 days of support, funded by the Government.</p><p> </p><p>This support meets and exceeds England and Wales’ obligations under Article 12 of the European Convention on Action Against Trafficking in Human Beings (ECAT), and Article 11 of the European Directive on Preventing and Combating Trafficking in Human Beings and Protecting its Victims. Support is tailored to individual needs and can include accommodation, subsistence, counselling, access to mental, physical and dental health services, and signposting to legal support.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687092/answer",,,,,,"2017-02-20T14:45:28.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687092/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687092/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-08","Human Trafficking: Prostitution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of Official Development Assistance funding was used to support people trafficked into the sex industry in the UK in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","63748"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687093","Home Office","false","2017-02-20","<p>The taskforce has met twice, 3 November 2016 and 12 January 2017 and includes representation from central Government and leading stakeholders. The taskforce aims to do more to bring perpetrators to justice and to support victims both domestically and overseas with the focus on four specific objectives:</p><p><br>o Bring efforts and resources targeted at modern slavery in line with resources to tackle other forms of organised crime;<br>o increase and improve investigations into the perpetrators of modern slavery, through further education of law enforcement officers on the nature of modern slavery offences;<br>o improve successful prosecution levels with further education of prosecuting authorities on modern slavery; and<br>o improve international cooperation to tackle modern slavery.</p><p><br>We are already seeing progress in gathering intelligence on perpetrators of this vile crime and are developing our international response to tackle the threat overseas and strengthen law enforcement cooperation.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687093/answer",,,,,,"2017-02-20T12:41:21.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687093/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687093/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-08","Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the task force announced by the Prime Minister on 31 July 2016 to accelerate progress on tackling modern slavery.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","63763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687094","Home Office","false","2017-02-20","<p>As we set out in the Government's response to the Home Affairs Select Committee (HASC), we are committed to tackling the harm and exploitation that can be associated with prostitution and sex work, and believe that people who want to leave prostitution should be given every opportunity to escape it. Our response additionally sets out that the Government will work with other Government departments, researchers and academics to develop a comprehensive, impartial understanding of the nature, prevalence and composition of prostitution and sex work in England and Wales.</p><p>This report will form the basis to review the effectiveness of current legislation, including Sections 14 and 17 of the Policing and Crime Act 2009.</p><p>Data on Engagement and Support Orders made under section 17 of the Policing and Crime Act 2009 are not held centrally.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687094/answer",,,,,"63765 ; 63766","2017-02-20T13:14:51.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687094/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687094/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-08","Drugs: Rehabilitation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people have been referred to drug and alcohol dependency programmes under Section 17 of the Policing and Crime Act 2009 since that Act came into force.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","63764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687095","Home Office","false","2017-02-20","<p>As we set out in the Government's response to the Home Affairs Select Committee (HASC), we are committed to tackling the harm and exploitation that can be associated with prostitution and sex work, and believe that people who want to leave prostitution should be given every opportunity to escape it. Our response additionally sets out that the Government will work with other Government departments, researchers and academics to develop a comprehensive, impartial understanding of the nature, prevalence and composition of prostitution and sex work in England and Wales.</p><p>This report will form the basis to review the effectiveness of current legislation, including Sections 14 and 17 of the Policing and Crime Act 2009.</p><p>Data on Engagement and Support Orders made under section 17 of the Policing and Crime Act 2009 are not held centrally.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687095/answer",,,,,"63764 ; 63766","2017-02-20T13:14:51.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687095/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687095/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-08","Prostitution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the effectiveness of Section 17 of the Policing and Crime Act 2009 on improving safety and support for people involved in prostitution.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","63765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687096","Home Office","false","2017-02-20","<p>As we set out in the Government's response to the Home Affairs Select Committee (HASC), we are committed to tackling the harm and exploitation that can be associated with prostitution and sex work, and believe that people who want to leave prostitution should be given every opportunity to escape it. Our response additionally sets out that the Government will work with other Government departments, researchers and academics to develop a comprehensive, impartial understanding of the nature, prevalence and composition of prostitution and sex work in England and Wales.</p><p>This report will form the basis to review the effectiveness of current legislation, including Sections 14 and 17 of the Policing and Crime Act 2009.</p><p>Data on Engagement and Support Orders made under section 17 of the Policing and Crime Act 2009 are not held centrally.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687096/answer",,,,,"63764 ; 63765","2017-02-20T13:14:51.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687096/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687096/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-08","Human Trafficking: Prostitution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment her Department has made of the effectiveness of Section 14 of the Policing and Crime Act 2009.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","63766"
